\par \lquote Harry, m\rquote boy!\rquote  said a booming voice from behind them.
\par \lquote Oh, no,\rquote  muttered Harry. The three of them turned to see Professor Slughorn, who was wearing an enormous furry hat and overcoat with matching fur collar, clutching a large bag of crystallised pin
eapple and occupying at least a quarter of the shop.
\par \lquote Harry, that\rquote s three of my little suppers you\rquote ve missed now!\rquote  said Slughorn, poking him genially in the chest. \lquote It won\rquote t do, m\rquote boy, I\rquote m determined to have you! Miss Granger loves them, don\rquote 
t you?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes,\rquote  said Hermione helplessly, \lquote they\rquote re really \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote So why don\rquote t you come along, Harry?\rquote  demanded Slughorn.
\par \lquote Well, I\rquote ve had Quidditch practice, Professor,\rquote  said Harry, who had indeed been scheduling practices every time Slughorn had sent him a little violet-rib
bon-adorned invitation. This strategy meant that Ron was not left out and they usually had a laugh with Ginny imagining Hermione shut up with McLaggen and Zabini.
\par \lquote Well, I certainly expect you to win your first match after all this hard work!\rquote  said Slughorn. \lquote But a little recreation never hurt anybody. Now, how about Monday night, you can\rquote t possibly want to practise in this weather ...
\rquote 
\par \lquote I can\rquote t, Professor, I\rquote ve got \endash  er \endash  an appointment with Professor Dumbledore that evening.\rquote 
\par \lquote Unlucky again!\rquote  cried Slughorn dramatically. \lquote Ah, well ... you can\rquote t evade me for ever, Harry!\rquote 
\par And with a regal wave, he waddled out of the shop, taking as little notice of Ron as though he had been a display of Cockroach Cluster.
\par \lquote I can\rquote t believe you\rquote ve wriggled out of another one,\rquote  said Hermione, shaking her head. \lquote They\rquote re not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699 that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699 bad, you know ... they\rquote re even quite fun sometimes ...\rquote  But then she caught sight of Ron\rquote s expression. \lquote Oh, look \endash  they\rquote ve got Deluxe Sugar Quills 
\endash  those would last hours!\rquote 
\par Glad that Hermione had changed the subject, Harry showed much more interest in the new extra-large Sugar Quills than he would normally have done, but Ron continued to look moody and merely shrugged when Hermione asked him where he wanted to go next.

\par \lquote Let\rquote s go to the Three Broomsticks,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote It\rquote ll be warm.\rquote 
\par They bundled their scarves back over their faces and left the sweet shop. The bitter wind was like knives on their faces after the sugary warmth of Honeydukes. The street was not very busy; nobody was lingering to chat, just hurry\-
ing towards their destinations. The exceptions were two men a little ahead of them, standing just outside the Three Broomsticks. One was very tall and thin; squinting through his rain-washed glasses Harry recognised the barman who worked in the other
 Hogsmeade pub, the Hog\rquote 
s Head. As Harry, Ron and Hermione drew closer, the barman drew his cloak more tightly around his neck and walked away, leaving the shorter man to fumble with something in his arms. They were barely feet from him when Harry realised who the man was.

\par \lquote Mundungus!\rquote 
\par The squat, bandy-legged man with long straggly ginger hair jumped and dropped an ancient suitcase, which burst open, releasing what looked like the entire contents of a junk shop window.
\par \lquote Oh, \rquote ello, \rquote Arry,\rquote  said Mundungus Fletcher, with a most unconvincing stab at airiness. \lquote Well, don\rquote t let me keep ya.\rquote 
\par And he began scrabbling on the ground to retrieve the contents of his suitcase with every appearance of a man eager to be gone.
\par \lquote Are you selling this stuff?\rquote  asked Harry, watching Mundungus grabbing an assortment of grubby-looking objects from the ground.
\par \lquote Oh, well, gotta scrape a living,\rquote  said Mundungus. \lquote Gimme that!\rquote 
\par Ron had stooped down and picked up something silver.
\par \lquote Hang on,\rquote  Ron said slowly. \lquote This looks familiar \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Thank you!\rquote  said Mundungus, snatching the goblet out of Ron\rquote s hand and stuffing it back into the case. \lquote Well, I\rquote ll see you all \endash  OUCH!\rquote 
\par Harry had pinned Mundungus against the wall of the pub by the throat. Holding him fast with one hand, he pulled out his wand.
\par \lquote Harry!\rquote  squealed Hermione.
\par \lquote You took that from Sirius\rquote s house,\rquote  said Harry, who was almost nose-to-nose with Mundungus and was breathing in an unpleasant smell of old tobacco and spirits. \lquote That had the Black family crest on it.\rquote 
\par \lquote I \endash  no \endash  what \endash ?\rquote  spluttered Mundungus, who was turning slowly purple.
\par \lquote What did you do, go back the night he died and strip the place?\rquote  snarled Harry.
\par \lquote I \endash  no \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Give it to me!\rquote 
\par \lquote Harry, you mustn\rquote t!\rquote  shrieked Hermione, as Mundungus started to turn blue.
\par There was a bang and Harry felt his hands fly off Mundungus\rquote s throat. Gasping and spluttering, Mundungus seized his fallen case, then \endash  CRACK \endash  he Disapparated.
\par Harry swore at the top of his voice, spinning on the spot to see where Mundungus had gone.
\par \lquote COME BACK, YOU THIEVING \endash !\rquote 
\par \lquote There\rquote s no point, Harry.\rquote 
\par Tonks had appeared out of nowhere, her mousy hair wet with sleet.
\par \lquote Mundungus will probably be in London by now. There\rquote s no point yelling.\rquote 
\par \lquote He\rquote s nicked Sirius\rquote s stuff! Nicked it!\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, but still,\rquote  said Tonks, who seemed perfectly untroubled by this piece of information, \lquote you should get out of the cold.\rquote 
\par She watched them through the door of the Three Broomsticks. The moment he was inside, Harry burst out, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699 \lquote He was nicking Sirius\rquote s stuff!\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699 
\par \lquote I know, Harry, but please don\rquote t shout, people are staring,\rquote  whispered Hermione. \lquote Go and sit down, I\rquote ll get you a drink.\rquote 
\par Harry was still fuming when Hermione returned to their table a few minutes later holding three bottles of Butter\-beer.
\par \lquote Can\rquote t the Order control Mundungus?\rquote  Harry demanded of the other two in a furious whisper. \lquote Can\rquote t they at least stop him stealing everything that\rquote s not fixed down when he\rquote s at Headquarters?\rquote 
\par \lquote Shh!\rquote  said Hermione desperately, looking around to make sure nobody was listening; there were a couple of warlocks sitting close by who were staring at Harry with great interest, and Zabini was lolling against a pillar not far away. 
\lquote Harry, I\rquote d be annoyed too, I know it\rquote s your things he\rquote s stealing \endash \rquote 
\par Harry gagged on his Butterbeer; he had momentarily forgotten that he owned number twelve, Grimmauld Place.
\par \lquote Yeah, it\rquote s my stuff!\rquote  he said. \lquote No wonder he wasn\rquote t pleased to see me! Well, I\rquote m going to tell Dumbledore what\rquote s going on, he\rquote s the only one who scares Mundungus.\rquote 
\par \lquote Good idea,\rquote  whispered Hermione, clearly pleased that Harry was calming down. \lquote Ron, what are you staring at?\rquote 
\par \lquote Nothing,\rquote  said Ron, hastily looking away from the bar, but Harry knew he was trying to catch the eye of the curvy and attractive barmaid, Madam Rosmerta, for whom he had long nursed a soft spot.
\par \lquote I expect \'93nothing\'94\rquote s in the back getting more Firewhisky,\rquote  said Hermione waspishly.
\par Ron ignored this jibe, sipping his drink in what he evi\-dently considered to be a dignified silence. Harry was think\-ing about Sirius, and how he had hated 
those silver goblets anyway. Hermione drummed her fingers on the table, her eyes flickering between Ron and the bar.
\par The moment Harry drained the last drops in his bottle she said, \lquote Shall we call it a day and go back to school, then?\rquote 
\par The other two nodded;
 it had not been a fun trip and the weather was getting worse the longer they stayed. Once again they drew their cloaks tightly around them, rearranged their scarves, pulled on their gloves; then followed Katie Bell and a friend out of the pub and back up
 the High Street. Harry\rquote s thoughts strayed to Ginny as they trudged up the road to Hogwarts through the frozen slush. They had not met up with her, undoubtedly, thought Harry, because she and Dean were cosily closeted in Madam Puddifoot\rquote 
s teashop, that haunt of happy couples. Scowling, he bowed his head against the swirl\-ing sleet and trudged on.
\par It was a little while before Harry became aware that the voices of Katie Bell and her friend, which were being carried back to him on the wind, had become shriller 
and louder. Harry squinted at their indistinct figures. The two girls were having an argument about something Katie was holding in her hand.
\par \lquote It\rquote s nothing to do with you, Leanne!\rquote  Harry heard Katie say.
\par They rounded a corner in the lane, sleet coming thick and fast, blurring Harry\rquote 
s glasses. Just as he raised a gloved hand to wipe them, Leanne made to grab hold of the package Katie was holding; Katie tugged it back and the package fell to the ground.
\par At once, Katie rose into the air, not as Ron had done, su
spended comically by the ankle, but gracefully, her arms outstretched, as though she were about to fly. Yet there was something wrong, something eerie ... her hair was whipped around her by the fierce wind, but her eyes were closed and her face was quite 
empty of expression. Harry, Ron, Hermione and Leanne had all halted in their tracks, watching.
\par Then, six feet above the ground, Katie let out a terrible scream. Her eyes flew open but whatever she could see, or whatever she was feeling, was clearly causing 
her terrible anguish. She screamed and screamed; Leanne started to scream too, and seized Katie\rquote s ankles, trying to tug her back to the ground. Harry, Ron and Hermione rushed forwards to help, but even as they grabbed Katie\rquote 
s legs, she fell on top of them; Harry and Ron managed to catch her but she was writhing so much they could hardly hold her. Instead they lowered her to the ground where she thrashed and screamed, apparently unable to recognise any of them.
\par Harry looked around; the landscape seemed deserted.
\par \lquote Stay there!\rquote  he shouted at the others over the howling wind. \lquote I\rquote m going for help!\rquote 
\par He began to sprint towards the school; he had never seen anyone behave as Katie had just done and could not think what had caused it; he hurtled round a bend in the lane and collided with what seemed to be an enormous bear on its hind legs.
\par \lquote Hagrid!\rquote  he panted, disentangling himself from the hedge\-row into which he had fallen.
\par \lquote Harry!\rquote  said Hagrid, who had sleet trapped in his eyebrows and beard, and was wearing his great, shaggy beaverskin coat. \lquote Jus\rquote  bin visitin\rquote  Grawp, he\rquote s comin\rquote  on so well yeh wouldn\rquote  \endash \rquote 

\par \lquote Hagrid, someone\rquote s hurt back there, or cursed, or some\-thing \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Wha\rquote ?\rquote  said Hagrid, bending lower to hear what Harry was saying over the raging wind.
\par \lquote Someone\rquote s been cursed!\rquote  bellowed Harry.
\par \lquote Cursed? Who\rquote s bin cursed \endash  not Ron? Hermione?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, it\rquote s not them, it\rquote s Katie Bell \endash  this way ...\rquote 
\par Together they ran back along the lane. It took them no time to find the little group of people around Katie, who was still writhing and screaming on the ground; Ron, Hermione and Leanne were all trying to quieten her.
\par \lquote Get back!\rquote  shouted Hagrid. \lquote Lemme see her!\rquote 
\par \lquote Something\rquote s happened to her!\rquote  sobbed Leanne. \lquote I don\rquote t know what \endash \rquote 
\par Hagrid stared at Katie for a second, then, without a word, bent down, scooped her into his arms and ran off towards the castle with her. Within seconds, Katie\rquote s piercing screams had died away and the only sound was the roar of the wind.
\par Hermione hurried over to Katie\rquote s wailing friend and put an arm around her.
\par \lquote It\rquote s Leanne, isn\rquote t it?\rquote 
\par The girl nodded.
\par \lquote Did it just happen all of a sudden, or \endash ?\rquote 
\par \lquote It was when that package tore,\rquote  sobbed Leanne, pointing at the now sodden brown-paper pac
kage on the ground, which had split open to reveal a greenish glitter. Ron bent down, his hand outstretched, but Harry seized his arm and pulled him back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699 \lquote Don\rquote t touch it!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699 
\par He crouched down. An ornate opal necklace was visible, poking out of the paper.
\par \lquote I\rquote ve seen that before,\rquote  said Harry, staring at the thing. \lquote It was on display in Borgin and Burkes ages ago. The label said it was cursed. Katie must have touched it.\rquote 
 He looked up at Leanne, who had started to shake uncontrollably. \lquote How did Katie get hold of this?\rquote 
\par \lquote Well, that\rquote 
s why we were arguing. She came back from the bathroom in the Three Broomsticks holding it, said it was a surprise for somebody at Hogwarts and she had to deliver it. She looked all funny when she said it ... oh no, oh no, I bet she\rquote d b
een Imperiused, and I didn\rquote t realise!\rquote 
\par Leanne shook with renewed sobs. Hermione patted her shoulder gently.
\par \lquote She didn\rquote t say who\rquote d given it to her, Leanne?\rquote 
\par \lquote No ... she wouldn\rquote t tell me ... and I said she was being stupid and not to take it up to school, but she just wouldn\rquote t listen and ... and then I tried to grab it from her ... and \endash  and \endash \rquote 
 Leanne let out a wail of despair.
\par \lquote We\rquote d better get up to school,\rquote  said Hermione, her arm still around Leanne, \lquote we\rquote ll be able to find out how she is. Come on ...\rquote 
\par Harry hesitated for a moment, then pulled his scarf from around his face and, ignoring Ron\rquote s gasp, carefully covered the necklace in it and picked it up.
\par \lquote We\rquote ll need to show this to Madam Pomfrey,\rquote  he said.
\par As they followed Hermione and Leanne up the road, Harry was thinking furiously. They had just entered the grounds when he spoke, unable to keep his thoughts to himself any longer.
\par \lquote Malfoy knows about this necklace. It was in a case at Borgin and Burkes four years ago, I saw him having a good look at it while I was hiding from him and his dad. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699 This}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid7101699  is what he was buying that day when we followed him! He remembered it and he went back for it!\rquote 
\par \lquote I \endash  I dunno, Harry,\rquote  said Ron hesitantly. \lquote Loads of people go to Borgin and Burkes ... and didn\rquote t that girl say Katie got it in the girls\rquote  bathroom?\rquote 
\par \lquote She said she came back from the bathroom with it, she didn\rquote t necessarily get it in the bathroom itself \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote McGonagall!\rquote  said Ron warningly.
\par Harry looked up. Sure enough, Professor McGonagall was hurrying down the stone steps through swirling sleet to meet them.
\par \lquote Hagrid says you four saw what happened to Katie Bell \endash  upstairs to my office at once, please! What\rquote s that you\rquote re hold\-ing, Potter?\rquote 
\par \lquote It\rquote s the thing she touched,\rquote  said Harry.
\par \lquote Good Lord,\rquote  said Professor McGonagall, looking alarmed as she took the necklace from Harry. \lquote No, no, Filch, they\rquote re with me!\rquote 
 she added hastily, as Filch came shuffling eagerly across the Entrance Hall holding his Secrecy Sensor aloft. \lquote Take this necklace to Professor Snape at once, but be sure not to touch it, keep it wrapped in the scarf!\rquote 
\par Harry and the others followed Professor McGonagall upstairs and into her office. The sleet-spattered windows were rattling in their frames and the room was 
chilly despite the fire crackling in the grate. Professor McGonagall closed the door and swept round her desk to face Harry, Ron, Hermione and the still-sobbing Leanne.
\par \lquote Well?\rquote  she said sharply. \lquote What happened?\rquote 
\par Haltingly, and with many pauses while she at
tempted to control her crying, Leanne told Professor McGonagall how Katie had gone to the bathroom in the Three Broomsticks and returned holding the unmarked package, how Katie had seemed a little odd and how they had argued about the advis\-
ability of agreeing to deliver unknown objects, the argument culminating in the tussle over the parcel, which tore open. At this point, Leanne was so overcome there was no getting another word out of her.
\par \lquote All right,\rquote  said Professor McGonagall, not unkindly, \lquote go up to the hospital wing, please, Leanne, and get Madam Pomfrey to give you something for shock.\rquote 
\par When she had left the room, Professor McGonagall turned back to Harry, Ron and Hermione.
\par \lquote What happened when Katie touched the necklace?\rquote 
\par \lquote She rose up in the air,\rquote  said Harry, before either Ron or Hermione could speak. \lquote And then began to scream, and collapsed. Professor, can I see Professor Dumbledore, please?\rquote 
\par \lquote The Headmaster is away until Monday, Potter,\rquote  said Professor McGonagall, looking surprised.
\par \lquote Away?\rquote  Harry repeated angrily.
\par \lquote Yes, Potter, away!\rquote  said Professor McGonagall tartly. \lquote But anything you have to say about this horrible business can be said to me, I\rquote m sure!\rquote 
\par For a split second, Harry hesitated. Professor McGonagall did not invite confidences; Dumbledore,
 though in many ways more intimidating, still seemed less likely to scorn a theory, however wild. This was a life and death matter, though, and no moment to worry about being laughed at.
\par \lquote I think Draco Malfoy gave Katie that necklace, Professor.\rquote 
\par On one side of him, Ron rubbed his nose in apparent embarrassment; on the other, Hermione shuffled her feet as though quite keen to put a bit of distance between herself and Harry.
\par \lquote That is a very serious accusation, Potter,\rquote  said Professor McGonagall, after a shocked pause. \lquote Do you have any proof?\rquote 
\par \lquote No,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote but ...\rquote  and he told her about following Malfoy to Borgin and Burkes and the conversation they had overheard between him and Borgin.
\par When he had finished speaking, Professor McGonagall looked slightly confused.
\par \lquote Malfoy took something to Borgin and Burkes for repair?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, Professor, he just wanted Borgin to tell him how to mend something, he didn\rquote t have it with him. But that\rquote s not the point, the thing is that he bought something at the same time and I think it was that necklace \endash \rquote 

\par \lquote You saw Malfoy leaving the shop with a similar package?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, Professor, he told Borgin to keep it in the shop for him \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote But, Harry,\rquote  Hermione interrupted, \lquote Borgin asked him if he wanted to take it with him, and Malfoy said \'93no\'94 \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Because he didn\rquote t want to touch it, obviously!\rquote  said Harry angrily.
\par \lquote What he actually said was, \'93How would I look carrying that down the street?\'94,\rquote  said Hermione.
\par \lquote Well, he would look a bit of a prat carrying a necklace,\rquote  interjected Ron.
\par \lquote Oh, Ron,\rquote  said Hermione despairingly, \lquote it would be all wrapped up, so he wouldn\rquote t have to touch it, and quite easy to hide inside a cloak, so nobody would see it! I think what\-
ever he reserved at Borgin and Burkes was noisy or bulky; something he knew would draw attention to him if he carried it down the street \endash  and in any case,\rquote  she pressed on loudly, before Harry could interrupt, \lquote 
I asked Borgin about the neck\-lace, don\rquote t you remember? When I went in to try and find out what Malfoy had asked him to keep, I saw it there. And Borgin just told me the price, he didn\rquote t say it was already sold or anything \endash \rquote 

\par \lquote Well, you were being really obvious, he realised what you were up to within about five seconds, of course he wasn\rquote t going to tell you \endash  anyway, Malfoy could\rquote ve sent off for it since \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote That\rquote s enough!\rquote  said Professor McGonagall, as Hermione opened her mouth to retort, looking furious. \lquote 
Potter, I appreciate you telling me this, but we cannot point the finger of blame at Mr Malfoy purely because he visited the shop where this necklace might have been purchased. The same is probably true of hundreds of people \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote \endash  that\rquote s what I said \endash \rquote  muttered Ron.
\par \lquote \endash  and in any case, we have put stringent security measures in place this year, I do not believe that necklace can possibly have entered this school without our knowledge \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote \endash  but \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote \endash  and what is more,\rquote  said Professor McGonagall, with an air of awful finality, \lquote Mr Malfoy was not in Hogsmeade today.\rquote 
\par Harry gaped at her, deflating.
\par \lquote How do you know, Professor?\rquote 
\par \lquote Because he was doing detention with me. He has now failed to complete his Transfiguration homework twice in a row. So, thank you for telling me your suspicions, Potter,\rquote  she said as she marched past them, \lquote 
but I need to go up to the hospital wing now to check on Katie Bell. Good day to you all.\rquote 
\par She held open her office door. They had no choice but to file past her without another word.
\par Harry was angry with the other two for siding with McGonagall; nevertheless, he felt compelled to join in once they started discussing what had happened.
\par \lquote So who do you reckon Katie was supposed to give the necklace to?\rquote  asked Ron, as they climbed the stairs to the common room.
\par \lquote Goodness only knows,\rquote  said Hermione. \lquote But whoever it was has had a narrow escape. No one could have opened that package without touching the necklace.\rquote 
\par \lquote It could\rquote ve been meant for loads of people,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote Dumbledore \endash  the Death Eaters would love to get rid of him, he must be one of their top targets. Or Slughorn \endash  Dumbledore reckons Voldemort really wante
d him and they can\rquote t be pleased that he\rquote s sided with Dumbledore. Or \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Or you,\rquote  said Hermione, looking troubled.
\par \lquote Couldn\rquote t have been,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote or Katie would\rquote ve just turned round in the lane and given it to me, wouldn\rquote t she? I was behind her all the 
way out of the Three Broomsticks. It would have made much more sense to deliver the parcel out\-side Hogwarts, what with Filch searching everyone who goes in and out. I wonder why Malfoy told her to take it into the castle?\rquote 
\par \lquote Harry, Malfoy wasn\rquote t in Hogsmeade!\rquote  said Hermione, actually stamping her foot in frustration.
\par \lquote He must have used an accomplice, then,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote Crabbe or Goyle \endash  or, come to think of it, another Death Eater, he\rquote ll have loads better cronies than Crabbe and Goyle now he\rquote s joined up \endash \rquote 

\par Ron and Hermione exchanged looks that plainly said \lquote there\rquote s no point arguing with him\rquote .
\par \lquote Dilligrout,\rquote  said Hermione firmly, as they reached the Fat Lady.
